liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Federal Treasurer Jim Chalmers says the national economy is prepared to take on global headwinds, following data showing Australia outperforming international peers. Australia had higher employment growth during the Albanese government's first year in office than other major economies, according to new data from the Treasury Department. Between May 2022 and May 2023, 465,000 jobs were created, the highest number for any new government on record. In the year since May 2022, Australia recorded 3.4 percent employment growth. That compares with: 2.7 per cent in the US 1.8 per cent in Canada 1.5 per cent in Italy 0.8 per cent in Germany 0.3 per cent in Japan Chalmers says while the economy faces challenges, the country is in a strong position. "This is a remarkable achievement for the economy and for the Australian people," he says.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Treasurer Jim Chalmers trumpets employment growth numbers

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Nominees for the 63rd Logie Awards have just been announced at Sydney's Museum of Contemporary Art. The ABC's Leigh Sales, Mark Coles Smith and Shaun Micallef are all up for the Gold Logie, but face some stiff competition from the likes of Hamish Blake, Julia Morris and Osher Günsberg. Blake and Morris are also nominated for Most Popular Presenter, as is Micallef and the ABC's Tony Armstrong. This year's awards will be returning to Sydney for the first time in 37 years — at The Star on Sunday, July 30. Here are the Most Popular award categories — the Most Outstanding ones will follow in our next post.
